ial rule, and they are still vibrant and evocative today. This volume brings together a collection of innovative and fresh studies exploring different sites of imperial memory – those conceptual and real places where the memories of former colonial rulers and of former colonial subjects have crystallised into a lasting form. The volume explores how memory was built up, re-shaped and preserved across different empires, continents and centuries. It shows how it found concrete expression in stone and bronze, how it adhered to the stories that were told and retold about great individuals and how it was suppressed, denied and neglected.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memory. 0aColoniesxHistory. 0aImperialismxHistory. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBerlin's Botanical Garden.  aDavid Livingstone.  aImam Shamil.  aJan Pietersz Coen.  aJapan's post-imperial commemoration.  aKoregaon obelisk.  aMau Mau uprising.  aRobert Clive.  aThirteen Martyrs of Arad.  acolonial rule.  aimperial memory.  amonumental architecture.  anineteenth-century Algeria.1 aCreuzberger, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnthoven, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeppert, Dominik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeppert, Dominik, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoebelt, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuégan, Xavier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaiser, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoranyi, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumbhojkar, Shraddha, econtributor.